tic medicine, the improvisations of Gorgias, as well as the uses of kairos in Isocrates, Plato, Aristotle, Cicero, and the New Testament. Broad in its scope, the book also examines the distinctive philosophies of time reflected in Renaissance Humanism, Nineteenth-Century American Transcendentalism, Oriental art and ritual, and the application of kairos to contemporary philosophy, ethics, literary criticism, rhetorical theory, and composition pedagogy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aKairos (The Greek word). 0aRhetoric, Ancient. 0aRhetoric. 4aCommunication : Communication. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh1 aBaumlin, James S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaumlin, James S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBaumlin, Tita French, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenedikt, Amélie Frost, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnos, Richard Leo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEskin, Catherine R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Carolyn Eriksen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Joseph J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKinneavy, James L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMason, Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Carolyn R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoulakos, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRostagni, Augusto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSipiora, Phillip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat